##What changes have been made in Hong Kong since SARS hit the city?

Weixin Guokr42

Functional introductions, science and technology, are the language we speak to the world.

Many tourists come to Victoria，Ensenada la to punch in and take photos. I wonder if you have ever noticed the high-rise buildings along the Wan Chai Waterfront? Of these, the Hong Kong government headquarters in Tamar stands out because it looks like a giant doorway. Why design such a big hole? The reason begins with the Atypical pneumonia epidemic of 17 years ago.

Hong Kong government headquarters, Tamar, near Victoria，Ensenada La, Hong Kong | Sohu

Hong Kong: The challenge of a high-density mega-city

Hong Kong's rugged terrain, mountainous area accounted for 82% , the development of flat land is quite scarce, living environment is urgent. It is for this reason that the development model of high-density cities in Hong Kong has been established. Currently, 7.48 million people live on 1,100 square kilometers of land and 65.15 million tourists visit Hong Kong each year. An average of about 6,000 people per square kilometre in the urban area and 15,000 in Kwun Tong, the most densely populated area. 2.

A bird's-eye view of Hong Kong's dense urban architecture

The year 2003 was a memorable one for Hong Kong people, as the outbreak of infectious disease SARS in Hong Kong's community sickened 1,755 people and killed 299 in just four months from February to June 2003. According to the World Health Organization, Hong Kong is one of the most difficult places to control an epidemic due to its high population density and lack of clear boundaries between regions.

SARS has a far-reaching impact on Hong Kong's economy, people's livelihood and politics, especially on the improvement of public health awareness. Today, Hong Kong residents wear face masks when they have headache or fever. They wash their hands frequently. Hospitals, governments and schools are equipped with alcohol disinfectant and face masks, every building elevator, door, armrest and so on all adopt the measure that clean disinfects once an hour. In 2004, the Hong Kong Department of Health (DH) conducted a survey on personal and environmental hygiene. "after the SARS outbreak, respondents reported improvements in personal hygiene of 61.6% , home hygiene of 56.8% and overall environmental hygiene of 80.0% in Hong Kong. " 4

In addition to public health improvement measures, the government and designers are also aware of the importance of building environmental quality and climatic factors for public health and environmental hygiene, began A decade-long transformation to improve urban planning and architectural design 5.

In August 2003, the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong government led the Task Force on Clean Hong Kong to publish the report of the Task Force on Clean Hong kong-measures to improve environmental hygiene in Hong Kong, which identified three key areas for improvement:

Re-examine and improve the design of drainage and ventilation systems in building design;
Upgrading Urban Planning in the area of urban design, with air ventilation assessments and ventilation and landscape corridors especially for large-scale Planning and development projects;
Provision of more green and recreational sites in public housing ESTATES6.

Subsequently, the government launched a number of consultancy projects on urban climate and environment, issued a number of technical circulars and design guidelines, and gradually applied the findings of the scientific research on urban climate assessment to urban planning and architectural design.

Starting with urban planning and architectural design,
Let the sex flow into the city

Let's go back to the Tamar government headquarters in Victoria，Ensenada La. Why is there a big hole in the design of the building? This is because of the "Air Ventilation Assessment Methodology 7-8" introduced by the Hong Kong Planning Department in response to SARS. large-scale construction projects of this type are designed at the central government offices (Cgo) to avoid blocking air ventilation by a single row of screen towers, the requirement is not only to consider the ventilation requirements of their own buildings, but also to minimize the impact on the surrounding area of the wind environment, to ensure that the entire block of air circulation.

Because the central government offices (Cgo) is located on the waterfront, it is relatively open and has a good sea breeze. Behind the construction site is close to the major transport hub area on Hong Kong Island. There is a lot of pedestrian and vehicular traffic, in order to allow the sea breeze to penetrate the dense urban areas behind, it is necessary to create voids in the buildings, to make the massive buildings more permeable to the wind, and to ensure that the ground is open to the green space connecting the waterfront. Computer simulations and wind tunnel tests were carried out to determine how the hole was positioned, how wide it was, and how oriented it was.

Government headquarters, Tamar Kong | Sohu

Use of wind tunnel tests and hydrodynamic simulations to assess the wind environment around the proposed building design | Hong Kong Planning Department

Subsequently, in 2006-2012, the Hong Kong government conducted a comprehensive assessment of the urban environment and the human comfort of the residents, and launched project 9-10 of the urban climate map and wind environment assessment criteria. At present, the urban wind environment assessment, urban heat island effect, outdoor Human Comfort Assessment and ventilation corridor are considered in the new area planning and Old City reconstruction. Below is the ventilation corridor of the planned and reserved North New Development Area in Kwu Tung.

Kwu Tung North New Development Area Ventilation Corridor | Hong Kong government (2015)

To promote the research findings, the Planning Department of the Hong Kong government has updated the "Hong Kong Planning Standards and guidelines-chapter 11: Guidelines for Urban Design" , to introduce design measures to improve air ventilation to planners, architects and the general public through graphic presentation, it involves the control of building shape and layout, street direction, building group and height control, open space configuration of green space, etc. 11.

Specific measures such as: the direction of the city street should be in line with the main wind direction, at most not more than 30 degrees angle of tilt, so that the wind into the city. In addition, when new buildings are built along the waterfront, ensure that there is a certain distance between the different buildings to facilitate the penetration of sea breeze into the inland areas and avoid the formation of a screen-like screen.

Hong Kong urban design guidelines-executive summary | Planning Department, Hong Kong government (2005)

Subsequently, the Buildings Department (bd) of the Hong Kong government commissioned a research team to conduct a review of Hong Kong's building regulations and operational issues relating to the quality of urban living space, three key guidelines are proposed for new buildings: CONTROL OF AIR VENTILATION BETWEEN BUILDINGS TO FACILITATE air circulation within the city, and back-off of narrow streets to ensure air circulation in pedestrian areas, to improve the micro-climate environment and mitigate the urban heat island effect by increasing the green coverage of the buildings, two architectural design guidelines for professionals, "APP151-enhancing architectural design for a sustainable built environment" and "APP152-guidelines for sustainable building design" 12.

It is worth mentioning that this guideline, for the first time, classifies the height of high-rise buildings into low-rise (0-20m) , middle-rise (20-60m) and high-rise (above 60m) assessment areas for the majority of high-density high-rise buildings in Hong Kong, each floor area has specific quantitative calculation requirements for building spacing and voids.

Calculation of building ventilation and schematic Diagram 12

To prevent and control epidemic diseases, urban construction can not be ignored

As a consultant to the government on Air Ventilation assessment, I have been involved in a number of government urban environmental consultancy projects both at home and abroad over the past decade. Urban planning programmes can be effective for as little as 10 years and can last for decades or even centuries. If something goes wrong, it will be a waste of manpower and material resources.

The outbreak of SARS and the new pneumonia epidemic once again put in front of us how to better plan the cities of millions of people and provide a healthy living environment. It is worth examining the most basic natural and climatic factors in urban residential environment to ensure that the basic planning and design indicators such as sunshine, ventilation and drainage are in line with health protection.

How To better plan the cities of millions of people and provide a healthy living environment? | Pixabay

After SARS, urban planning and architectural design in Hong Kong focused on urban ventilation and air circulation, and actively considered the use of controlled urban space planning, strengthen the layout of ventilation corridors and open spaces of green space in dense urban areas, and control the architectural form from the perspective of three-dimensional space stratification, so as to be more transparent and more conducive to air circulation, improve outdoor air quality and comfortable living 13-14.

In the face of climate change, frequent transportation links, high population density and mega urban construction, there may be other emerging infectious diseases and other disasters in the future, there is an urgent need to consider and study the relationship and impact of spatial quality of urban planning on public health risks. It's a long road ahead!

By Ren Chao
